<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-03-08T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-03-08T03:00:00-05:00" n="59" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d59">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/8361: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-03-08T16:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">March 8,
                                        1927—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received March 8—9:20
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>200. Regarding commander in chief’s telegram of March 7th to the chief of
                            naval operations, 0007–1800, concerning prevention of Chinese factions’
                            naval fighting on the Whangpoo, I consider the Department’s 216,
                            September 13, 4 p.m., 1924,<note n="76" xml:id="d59fn76"><ref target="frus1924v01#pg_375"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                        Relations</hi>, 1924, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p.
                                    375</ref>.</note> applies and suggest that Admiral Williams be
                            instructed to cooperate with his foreign colleagues to that effect and
                            that I be authorized by telegraph to adopt this attitude should
                            necessity arise.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>